title mikroPhone seated as teacher; the SLC product named — Glow software on capable hardware, Sala broadcast the flagship
prompt Keaton pointed at mikrophone.net, then noted its performance is really limited and that we need an SLC product that still follows our compass -- write then ship.
think read mikroPhone honestly: a beautiful open-hardware, RISC-V-core, NLnet-funded privacy phone -- landing on Glow's own RISC-V horizon and mirroring the two-body split -- but performance-limited by design, which is exactly the price of total bespoke openness. Took Keaton's point as the decisive one: we do not fabricate performance-limited hardware to chase openness.
think turned the limit into the product answer: the SLC product is not a phone but Glow's sovereign anti-extraction software, shipped in Simple-Lovable-Complete laps on capable existing hardware (the /e/OS Fairphone), where capability comes from the silicon and sovereignty from our code. This also sidesteps mikroPhone's trade entirely rather than competing with it.
think named the flagship SLC product as Sala broadcast, and held it honestly against the three SLC questions: Simple (one loop -- record/replay, later carry/watch), Lovable (genuinely wanted by the musicians/creators this tree serves, sovereign, no platform between them and their audience), Complete (L1 already closes the loop -- Sala B0 green). Walked the whole compass (foundations, grain, witness-before-truth, civic audit) so it is not just a feature but a compass-true product.
think laid the SLC laps: L1 record+replay GREEN today (Sala B0, and proven on aarch64 at M0, so it already runs on the phone's architecture); L2 live carriage and L3 audience both horizon, honestly gated on Pool P0 -- no promise of live broadcast before that keystone lands.
think seated mikroPhone as a gratitude teacher with its licenses named (CERN OHL v1.2 hardware, GPLv2 software -- both reciprocal) and the clean-room boundary stated: study the design, never copy firmware or schematics; re-express in our own words. This is required attribution since I studied it, per the gratitude-licenses rule.
think this is "write then ship" -- an explicit ship instruction -- so unlike the prior held branches, this send does commit-push-merge to main per the send convention.
file gratitude/mikrophone.md -- new; mikroPhone teacher note, licenses + clean-room boundary + the performance-limit lesson
gratitude/README.md -- mikroPhone bullet added to the study shelf
